leads.lead_text: Lateral sepals erect and embracing the galea
Lateral sepals deflexed away from the galea
Rosette leaves encircling the base of the scape, often passing into cauline leaves
Rosette leaves not encircling the base of the scape, either present on side shoots or on non-flowering plants
Labellum apex with a small or large notch
Labellum apex entire
Labellum apex deeply notched
Labellum apex with a small inconspicuous notch
Rosette leaves tightly grouped at the base of the scape; petiolate
Rosette leaves grouped in a loose spiral in the basal third of the scape, usually sessile or subsessile
Labellum not protruding through the front of the sinus in the set position, either the tip just visible or the whole labellum enclosed and not visible
Distal quarter to half of the labellum protruding through the front of the sinus in the set position
Sepals all with filiform points of similar length
Dorsal sepal much shorter than the lateral sepals
Lateral sepals tightly embracing the galea, no lateral gap visible, flowers greenish
Lateral sepals loosely embracing the galea, leaving a lateral gap, flowers with dark brown suffusions
Flowers nodding slightly forward
Flowers erect or nodding manifestly forward
Apex of labellum acuminate; flowers to c. 3 cm long, appearing in Autumn; far East Gippsland
Apex of labellum blunt; flowers to c. 4 cm long, appearing in Spring; widespread
Flowers nodding manifestly forward; labellum scabrous
Flowers more or less erect; labellum smooth
Flower 5–6 cm long, labellum tip straight
Flower 3–3.5 cm long, labellum tip twisted prominently to one side
Sinus scabrous, flowers with copious brown suffusions
Sinus smooth, flowers mostly green and white, sometimes with brown-tipped galea
Labellum protruding prominently from the sinus in the set position; dorsal sepal ending in a filiform point exceeding the petals
Labellum tip just visible from the front, not protruding through the sinus; dorsal sepal blunt-tipped, not exceeding the petals
Labellum dark blue-green; sub-alpine watercourses
Labellum dark green to brownish, never blue-green
Flower to c. 2 cm long, lateral sepals tightly embracing the galea, no lateral gap visible
Flower 2.5 cm or more long, lateral sepals loosely embracing the galea leaving a lateral gap
Scape scabrid
Scape smooth
Flower to c. 3 cm long, sinus protruding prominently in an abrupt curve when viewed from the side, free points reflexed behind the galea
Flower 3–5 cm long, sinus protruding in a shallow curve when viewed from the side, free points erect above the galea
Flower 4–5 cm long, >12 mm wide; tip of galea curved to, or beyond, the horizontal
Flower 3–4 cm long, 8–12 mm wide; tip of galea more or less erect
Flower 5–8 cm long; dorsal sepal tip greatly exceeding the petals; stream banks, swamps and soaks, but not associated with Leptospermum lanigerum
Flower 3–4.5 cm long; dorsal sepal tip not greatly exceeding the petals; swampy Leptospermum lanigerum thickets
Rosette leaves only developed on non-flowering plants
Rosette leaves borne on a lateral growth at the base of the scape
Dorsal sepal acute to acuminate, lacking a filiform point
Dorsal sepal with a distinct filiform point at least 3 mm long
Petal margins prominently flared, dark red-brown, distal half of labellum linear-filiform with a slightly expanded apex
Petal margins decurved, green to light brown, labellum tapered in distal half but not linear-filiform, apex acute to subacute
Sinus V-shaped when viewed from the front
Sinus flat or raised when viewed from the front, often with a central notch
Labellum not protruding from the sinus in the set position, apex obtuse, truncate or slightly notched
Labellum protruding from the sinus in the set position, apex long-acuminate
Flower about 1–1.5 cm long; Leptospermum lanigerum thickets
Flower 2 cm or more long; habitat not as below
Flower 2–3 cm long, galea with a short curve, labellum 12–17 mm long
Flower 4.5–7 cm long, galea with a long, sweeping shallow curve, labellum 18–24 mm long
Sinus abruptly protruding and platform-like when viewed from the side
Sinus flat or shallowly mounded or curved when viewed from the side, never platform-like
Distal third of labellum protruding from the sinus in the set position
Labellum tip just visible through the sinus in the set position
Flower bluish-green and white, strongly inflated at the base, labellum 15–19 mm long
Flower green and white with red-brown suffusions in the galea, not strongly inflated at base, labellum 11–13 mm long
Dorsal sepal with a short filiform point only slightly exceeding the petals; sinus of lateral sepals v-notched when viewed from the front; petals green; mostly coastal scrubs
Dorsal sepal with a filiform point significantly exceeding the petals; sinus of lateral sepals not v-notched when viewed from the front; petals red-brown; widespread, usually inland
Flower 3 cm or more long
Flower 1.5–2.5 cm long
Sinus scabrid, labellum protruding prominently from the sinus in the set position; East Gippsland
Sinus smooth, labellum tip just visible in the set position; western Victoria
Labellum tip just visible in the set position
Labellum protruding prominently from the sinus in the set position
Flower erect, free points of lateral sepals erect
Flower semi-nodding, free points of lateral sepals recurved or lax
Labellum tip visible through the sinus in the set position
Labellum tip not visible through the sinus in the set position
Dorsal sepal not scabrous
Dorsal sepal scabrous
Scape narrowest at the base, widening upwards; ovaries long and swollen; flowers entirely green and white; flowers appearing in spring and summer; swampy habitats
Scape of equal width throughout; ovaries short and not swollen; flowers entirely green and white or with brownish petals; flowers appearing in autumn and winter; dry habitats
Sinus v-shaped when viewed from the front
Sinus flat with a small median notch when viewed from the front
Plants bearing up to 20 flowers; flowers angular and narrow, appearing in summer
Plants bearing up to 12 flowers; flowers rounded and plump, appearing in autumn and winter; southern Victoria
Rosette leaves pale green, to 6 mm long and 7 mm wide; flowers green and white with a reddish brown apex; tip of dorsal sepal and petals sparsely scabrous; south-west Victoria
Rosette leaves bluish green, to 25 mm long and 18 mm wide; flowers green, white and dark brown; most of the dorsal sepal and petals densely scabrous; northern Victoria
Labellum lamina filiform with an apical knob and numerous long yellow hairs
Labellum lamina flat, lacking an apical knob and yellow hairs
Stem leaves poorly developed and tightly sheathing the peduncle, rosette leaves encircling the base of the scape, sometimes withered at flowering
Stem leaves well-developed and spreading, rosette leaves only developed on non-flowering plants
Connate part of lateral sepals wider than galea; labellum with a tail-like basal appendage; flowers predominantly reddish
Connate part of lateral sepals about as wide as galea; labellum with a basal mound and lacking a basal appendage; flowers predominantly green
Petals each with a prominent basal flange which block off the base of the galea, labellum emerald green or dark reddish-brown
Petals each with a poorly developed basal flange which do not meet and block off the base of the galea, labellum yellowish or wholly brown often with a dark brown to blackish central stripe
Galea 11–16 mm long; labellum 5.5–7 mm long; synsepalum broad-oblong–elliptic; north-west Victoria in mallee habitats and dry woodlands near Ararat
Galea 15–22 mm long; labellum 6–8 mm long; synsepalum oblong or narrow elliptic; habitats various, but not found in mallee
Labellum and tips of sepals deep reddish-brown
Labellum and tips of sepals green
Galea 15–18 mm long, pale translucent green with dark green lines; synsepalum narrow oblong
Galea 17–22 mm long, dark green with darker lines; synsepalum narrow elliptic
Synsepalum ovate; petals without basal flanges, the anterior margin broadly curved; eastern Victoria between Benambra and Wulgulmerang
Synsepalum elliptic; petals with small basal flanges, the anterior margin straight or shallowly curved
Labellum appearing hairy with transparent acicular hairs over most of its surface; known only from the Grampians
Transparent acicular hairs mostly confined to the labellum base or absent
Labellum wholly brown or blackish, central stripe inconspicuous; near-coastal, often granite areas of eastern Victoria
Labellum cream to pale yellow (rarely light brown) with a conspicuous blackish central stripe
Labellum with numerous acicular hairs at the base
Labellum with few acicular hairs at the base
Flowers dark green with bright orange-brown tips on the sepals; north-east Victoria
Flowers pale green with light-brown tips on the sepals; widespread
Labellum 5–6 mm long, widest towards the apex, light brown with a dark central stripe; north-east Victoria
Labellum 4–5 mm long, of equal width throughout, yellowish with a black central stripe; western Victoria between Ballarat and the Grampians
Labellum lamina glabrous, thin and membranous, with a well-developed basal appendage
Labellum lamina bearing hairs, not membranous, often fleshy, covered with transparent siliceous cells, basal appendage poorly developed or absent (except in P. woollsii)
Labellum appendage erect, central ridge produced into a beak-like structure
Labellum appendage recurved, central ridge not produced into a beak-like structure
Plants often robust, to 30 cm tall; flowers heavily striped bluish-green and white; alpine and subalpine meadows of eastern Victoria
Plants more slender, usually less than 15 cm tall; flowers mostly bright green, not heavily striped; not found in alpine or subalpine environments
Galea 6–8 mm long; flowers crowded and overlapping; rosette leaves 3–8 mm wide; extremely rare in stony rise grasslands of western Victoria
Galea 7–9 mm long; flowers uncrowded, not usually overlapping; rosette leaves 8–15 mm wide; widespread, but not usually in stony rise grasslands
Labellum basal appendage green, apex obtuse
Labellum basal appendage dark blackish green, apex truncate to emarginate
Flowers crowded and overlapping; scape 7–16 cm tall; extremely rare in stony rise grasslands of western Victoria
Flowers uncrowded, not usually overlapping; scape 15–35 cm tall; widespread, but not usually in stony rise grasslands
Plants often robust, to 30 cm tall; flowers widely spaced, not overlapping; woodlands and grassland
Plants usually shorter, to 16 cm tall; flowers crowded and overlapping; grasslands
Scape 3–4 mm thick; extremely rare (possibly extinct) species from near Sale
Scape 1–3 mm thick
Labellum lamina oblong to obovate; central ridge of labellum appendage thin and not raised above the marginal ridges; basalt plains grassland north and west of Melbourne
Labellum lamina elliptical; central ridge of labellum appendage thick and raised above the marginal ridges; montane grassland and herbfield of East Gippsland
Dorsal sepal with a filiform point 3 mm or more long; labellum ovate, ovate-oblong or obovate, 4–7 mm long
Dorsal sepal with a filiform point 3 mm long or less; labellum oblong, to c. 4 mm long
Basal lobe of the labellum c. 3 mm long, filamentous tips of lateral sepals c. 10 cm or more long
Basal lobe of the labellum to c. 1 mm long, filamentous tips of lateral sepals less than 4 cm long
Labellum fleshy, with or without two (rarely 4) prominent basal hairs
Labellum thin-textured with 2 or 4 prominent porrect basal hairs 2.5–6 mm long
Tips of lateral sepals hooked forwards
Tips of lateral sepals deflexed or curved gently forwards, usually not hooked forwards
Dorsal sepal with decurved filiform point; proximal flanges of petals meeting and blocking off the base of the galea; labellum not or only partially visible from the side
Dorsal sepal with upcurved filiform point; proximal flanges of petals not meeting, leaving a gap in the base of the galea; labellum wholly visible from the side
Conjoined part of lateral sepals very broad, transverse elliptic to suborbicular, base truncate with sides more or less horizontal
Conjoined part of lateral sepals relatively narrow, ovate, base obtuse with sides curved downwards
Labellum ovate to obovate, 4.5–5.5 mm long, 2–2.3 mm wide; hairs on base of lateral sepals short
Labellum ovate-oblong, 4–4.5 mm long, c. 1.6 mm wide; hairs on base of lateral sepals quite long
Flowers dark reddish brown to almost black, often nodding; lateral sepals deeply concave at base
Flowers reddish brown with some green on galea, usually porrect; lateral sepals shallowly concave at base
Lateral sepals with filiform points >15 mm long; labellum more or less ovate, widest near base; mallee scrub in far north-west Victoria
Lateral sepals with filiform points <15 mm long; labellum more or less oblong, widest near middle; Eucalyptus/Callitris woodland near Beechworth in north-east Victoria
Flowers with green and colourless transparent bands; marginal hairs on proximal half of labellum as long or longer than labellum
Flowers predominantly brown or a mix of brown, olive and/or green; marginal hairs on proximal half of labellum shorter than labellum
Basal mound of labellum  with dense small hairs; pigmented parts of galea dark reddish-brown; labellum ovate-oblong; filiform point on dorsal sepal 5–6 mm long;
Basal mound of labellum without a crown of dense small hairs, but sparse and/or longer hairs to 1.5 mm long may be present; pigmented parts of galea greenish
Labellum ovate, basal mound with scattering of 4 sparse hairs  to 1.5 mm long on prominent basal mound, stony rise grasslands of western Victoria
Labellum obovate, basal mound with few or no hairs
Plant  9 –20 cm tall; labellum 4.8–5.7 mm long, 1.2–2.1 mm wide
Plant  18–58 cm tall; labellum 6.2–7.9 mm long, 1.7–2.9 mm wide
Scape 8 cm long or less, flowers spreading to deflexed, the free points of the lateral sepals often touching the ground
Scape usually more than 10 cm tall, flowers spreading to obliquely erect, free points of lateral sepals hanging well clear of the ground
Flowers mostly with green markings and suffusions
Flowers brown or a mix of brown, olive and/or green;
Flowers usually a mix of brown, olive and/or green stripes with translucent white markings; labellum upturned at the tip, with translucent grooves longitudinally in distal half
Flowers mostly brown with some colourless 'windows' in the galea; labellum lacking translucent grooves, without a prominently upturned tip
Rosette leaves to 6 mm wide, labellum up to 3.5 mm wide; riverine woodlands with clayey soils dominated by Black Box (Eucalyptus largiflorens)
Rosette leaves to 18 mm wide, labellum 3.5–4.5 mm wide; habitat not as above, soils freely-draining
Conjoined part of lateral sepals more or less flat with incurved margins; rosette leaves prominently veined; petals attenuate at base, long-acuminate at apex; far western Victoria
Conjoined part of lateral sepals concave; rosette leaves not prominently veined; petals not as above; widespread
Lateral sepals c. 4 mm wide, green and light brown, dull, swept back
Lateral sepals >5 mm wide, reddish brown, shiny, deflexed
Labellum obovate; lateral sepals ending in filiform points often >10 mm long; Beechworth area
Labellum oblong; lateral sepals ending in filiform points <10 mm long; mostly western Victoria
Galea 13–16 mm long; conjoined part of sepals at the widest point as wide as or wider than the galea
Galea less than 13 mm long (usually c. 10 mm); conjoined part of sepals at the widest point narrower than galea
Galea c. 16 mm long including an apical tip c. 2 mm long; lateral sepals c. 6 mm across, similar in width to galea, free part c. 8 mm long;
Galea c. 13 mm long including an apical tip c. 1.5 mm long; lateral sepals c. 7 mm across, slightly broader than galea, free part c. 7 mm long
Plants mostly <15 cm tall; galea <30 mm long; dorsal sepal lacking a filiform point; labellum hairs very dense
Plants mostly >15 cm tall; galea >30 mm long; dorsal sepal with an upturned filiform point; labellum hairs moderately dense
Apical knob on labellum usually green; galea 35–40 mm long; plants to 35 cm tall; Anglesea area
Apical knob on labellum brown; galea usually <35 mm long; plants to 25 cm tall; widespread
